TY  - JOUR
T1  - Economies of Scale, Domestic Divergences, and Potential Gains from Economic Integration in Ghana and the Ivory Coast
AU  - Pearson, Scott R.
AU  - Ingram, William D.
Y1  - 1980/10/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260918
DO  - 10.1086/260918
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 994
EP  - 1008
VL  - 88
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Economies of scale and domestic divergences offer an important scope for gains from industrial integration among developing countries. Underutilized industrial capacity, together with distorting policies and imperfections in factor markets, provides a rationale for countries to swap opportunities for industrial expansion. Through integration, Ghana and the Ivory Coast stand to achieve welfare gains of 33 and 22 percent of gross output in world prices. About two-fifths of these gains have their source in Viner's trade-creation effects, one-fifth in Corden's cost-reduction effects, and two-fifths in the newly suggested production effects.
AB  - Economies of scale and domestic divergences offer an important scope for gains from industrial integration among developing countries. Underutilized industrial capacity, together with distorting policies and imperfections in factor markets, provides a rationale for countries to swap opportunities for industrial expansion. Through integration, Ghana and the Ivory Coast stand to achieve welfare gains of 33 and 22 percent of gross output in world prices. About two-fifths of these gains have their source in Viner's trade-creation effects, one-fifth in Corden's cost-reduction effects, and two-fifths in the newly suggested production effects.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260918
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260918
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Theory of Vertical Control with Variable Proportions
AU  - Mallela, Parthasaradhi
AU  - Nahata, Babu
Y1  - 1980/10/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260919
DO  - 10.1086/260919
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1009
EP  - 1025
VL  - 88
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The effect of vertical integration by an input monopolist on the price of the final product and the derived demands are examined when the production is of CES and the demand for the final product is of constant elasticity. The results are proved by analytical methods. Specifically, when the elasticity of substitution is less than one, the price of the final product can decrease but, regardless of any conditions, the derived demand for the nonmonopolized input decreases. However, that of monopolized input decreases if and only if the elasticity of substitution exceeds the elasticity of demand.
AB  - The effect of vertical integration by an input monopolist on the price of the final product and the derived demands are examined when the production is of CES and the demand for the final product is of constant elasticity. The results are proved by analytical methods. Specifically, when the elasticity of substitution is less than one, the price of the final product can decrease but, regardless of any conditions, the derived demand for the nonmonopolized input decreases. However, that of monopolized input decreases if and only if the elasticity of substitution exceeds the elasticity of demand.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260919
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260919
Y2  - 2024/03/22
